2 limitation, guardians ad litem, mediators and employees of the
3 court; and
4 (b) Comply with any applicable requirements of the Violence
5 Against Women Act Reauthorization Act of 2022, Pub. L. No. 117-
6 103, 34 U.S.C. § 12291 et seq.
7 3. On or before January 1 of each year, the Court
8 Administrator shall prepare and submit to the Director of the
9 Legislative Counsel Bureau for transmittal to Legislature, or if the
10 Legislature is not in session, the Joint Interim Standing
11 Committee on the Judiciary, an annual report concerning the
12 instruction provided pursuant to this section. The report must
13 include, without limitation:
14 (a) The title of any course offered by the National Council of
15 Juvenile and Family Court Judges in the immediately preceding
16 year that satisfies the requirements of subsection 2; and
17 (b) The number of persons who attended each such course.
18 4. As used in this section:
19 (a) “Child custody proceeding” means a proceeding in which
20 legal custody, physical custody or visitation with respect to a child
21 is at issue. The term:
22 (1) Includes a proceeding for divorce, separation, paternity,
23 child support, termination of parental rights and protection from
24 domestic violence in which the issue may appear.
25 (2) Does not include a delinquency proceeding conducted
26 pursuant to title 5 of NRS or a proceeding held pursuant to
27 chapter 432B of NRS.
28 (b) “Judge” means a judge of the district court and any other
29 officer of the Judicial Branch of this State, including, without
30 limitation, a magistrate, master or referee.
31 Sec. 4. The provisions of subsection 1 of NRS 218D.380 do
32 not apply to any provision of this act which adds or revises a
33 requirement to submit a report to the Legislature.
34 Sec. 5. This act becomes effective on July 1, 2025.
